WordPress is an award-winning web software, used by millions of webmasters worldwide for building their website or blog. SiteGround is proud to host this particular WordPress installation and provide users with multiple resources to facilitate the management of their WP websites:

Expert WordPress Hosting

SiteGround provides superior WordPress hosting focused on speed, security and customer service. We take care of WordPress sites security with unique server-level customizations, WP auto-updates, and daily backups. We make them faster by regularly upgrading our hardware, offering free CDN with Railgun and developing our SuperCacher that speeds sites up to 100 times! And last but not least, we provide real WordPress help 24/7! Learn more about SiteGround WordPress hosting

Wordpress tutorial and knowledgebase articles

WordPress is considered an easy to work with software. Yet, if you are a beginner you might need some help, or you might be looking for tweaks that do not come naturally even to more advanced users. SiteGround WordPress tutorial includes installation and theme change instructions, management of WordPress plugins, manual upgrade and backup creation, and more. If you are looking for a more rare setup or modification, you may visit SiteGround Knowledgebase.

Free WordPress themes

SiteGround experts not only develop various solutions for WordPress sites, but also create unique designs that you could download for free. SiteGround WordPress themes are easy to customize for the particular use of the webmaster.

Future Plans

Healthcare awareness: systematic health talks will be conducted in batches for all patients who visit medical camps, with the sole purpose of uplifting health awareness

Ophthalmology: to get a team of ophthalmologists to help assess and screen patients with diabetic retinopathy, glaucoma, cataract and refractions, and engage in education and early intervention. Future equipment: A slit lamp.

Mobile pathology: A portable laboratory to provide value in our screening and help detect nutritional anaemias, chronic infections, renal diseases, cholesterol issues and complications of lifestyle disease. Once detected, emphasis is on education and early intervention. Future equipment: A mobile lab.

Ultrasound services: to help provide quality screening for rural villagers for gynaecology diseases, as well as pregnant mothers, and ensure that that womens health in rural areas are not neglected due to lack of education or poor socioeconomic conditions. Future equipment: A portable ultrasound machine.

The town itself comprises two rows of shophouses. The wet market in the town centre, has been abandoned by traders in favour of the bigger and better one at Kuala Kubu Baru town.

item.title: Kerling Mobile Medical Camp 16 December 2018
item.dc:creator: cp3402grp11
item.content:encoded:
Kerling is a  small town in Hulu Selangor, famous for its tin mines and rubber plantations. Kerling has always been a small town. It played second fiddle to nearby areas like Kuala Kubu Baru and Rasa in the heydays of tin mining. These days, especially on weekends, people visit Kerling for it famous hot spring. While some rubber plantations still stand, many have made way for either palm oil plantations or small housing estates.

This was the 2nd Mobile Medical Camp held there this time with a more stronger group of volunteers. About 35 of the dedicated volunteers comprising of doctors, dentists, pharmacists, dermatologist , medical assistants and optometrist were present to provide their services. More than 280 local residents of Kerling town received the free medical screening and relevant medication from the medical officers. Any of them were follow-up cases from the previous visit in January 2018.

item.title: Dengkil Orang Asli Mobile Medical Camp 13 January 2019
item.dc:creator: cp3402grp11
item.content:encoded:
On 13 Jan 2019, we were privileged to serve the Orang Asli community in Dengkil, Selangor. Dengkil is a mukim in Sepang District, Selangor, Malaysia.

The town lies between Cyberjaya and the Multimedia Super Corridor to the north, and Salak Tinggi to the south. Hidden between Putrajaya and Cyberjaya, a community of Temuan orang asli is living in isolation sandwiched by modern living. They have travel some 17km from their small wooden house to a government clinic in Dengkil if anyone fell ill.

Early communications with village elders revealed that many of the members of the villagers were seeking medical screening and medical attention. Often, these orang asli communities are situated far from major cities and as a result, have a difficult time finding quality healthcare as they need it. These communities are often under served and as results they face various challenges living a normal life.

A team was set up to run a mobile medical camp event at Dengkil. The team consisted of 9 doctors, 2 registered nurses, 3 pharmacists and a number of other volunteers from various backgrounds. Three of our volunteers travelled all the way from Singapore to participate in this camp. The objective of this medical camp was to provide free health screening on lifestyle related diseases and consultation based on patients needs The programme enables the community to undergo general health screening for non-communicable diseases such as diabetes and high blood pressure, among others.

More than 90 individuals were screened, and the team took every effort to meet and address all of their medical concerns. We spoke about healthy lifestyle, healthy eating habits and also recorded the BMI and nourishment status of each child in the village. We will be monitoring these patients and do a follow up with then during our next visit.

General conclusion drawn was that most children in this village do not have proper breakfast, having poor appetite and poor memory due to various reasons.

The success of these camps depends on our volunteers. Their time, effort, and fundraising is what keeps these life-saving camps alive. Medical students who attend the camps report the experience as having a massive impact on their personal and professional development and find it very rewarding indeed.

Statistics:

14 Medical volunteers
10 auxiliary volunteers
90 patients screened
6 specialties offered

item.title: Kalumpang - Mobile Medical Camp 23 June 2019
item.dc:creator: cp3402grp11
item.content:encoded:
Kalumpang Campus is under the auspices of MySkills Foundation of Malaysia who are working towards transforming At-Risk Youths, equipping them with the right skills and placing them with proper jobs so they can be gainfully employed.

We for the first time organized this free medical camp at Kalumpang Campus, co-organizing with Sai Ananda Nilayam. Sai Ananda Nilayam is a noble spiritual movement envisioned to provide voluntary medical assistance for almost 15 years. From bi-annual camps, they have grown to organize on a monthly basis and at times going to various remote regions of the country giving free medical assistance to people who are unable to get them.

The town Kalumpang has a population of about 3,000. Slightly over an hours drive from Kuala Lumpur, the town sits on the fringe of Selangor and to some city dwellers, it is a retreat they escape to over the weekend. The whole town has a mixture of Malay and Chinese villages coming from diverse economic background.

Medical screening and medical attention and awareness on good hygiene practices were given to the students of this campus. Many of our students were from dysfunctional environment that lack basic human values and personal hygiene. They face tremendous challenges to overcome these difficulties just to get back on track to lead a normal life.

About 30 of the dedicated volunteers comprising of doctors, dentists, pharmacists, dermatologist , medical assistants and optometrist were present to provide their services. More than 150 students and local residents of Kalumpang town received the free medical screening and relevant medication from the medical officers.

Statistics:
30 Medical volunteers
20 auxiliary volunteers
150 patients screened
6 specialties offered
